.","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Isenburg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of German or Jewish   Eisenberg  .","German: habitational name from the name of a medieval castle in the southern part of Hesse, the origin of a long line of nobility from the 12th century into the 21st century."],"variants":[{"name":"Eisenberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Moshe, Isadore, Akiva, Aron, Avner, Chaim, Emanuel, Isidor.","German: habitational name from any of several places so named, from Middle High German <i>īsen</i> ‘iron’ + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of 1."]}]},{"name":"Gerlach","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>lach</i> ‘sport’. St Gerlach was a hermit who lived near Valkenburg in the 12th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gerlach","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>lach</i> ‘sport’. St Gerlach was a hermit who lived near Valkenburg in the 12th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gerlach Gerlach II Von Isenburg was born in 1177, in Neuerburg, Bitburg, Rhineland, Prussia. He had at least 1 daughter with Juette Countess of Are Isenburg."},"et":{"1177–":"1177–Surnud","1181–Female":"1181–Surnud","1203–1267":"1203–1267","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1203":"1203","1267":"1267","1177":"1177","1181":"1181","Neuerburg, Rheinland, Prussia":"Neuerburg, Kreis Bitburg, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Neu-Isenburg, Hesse-Nassau, Germany":"Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1177–":"1177–Kuollut","1181–Female":"1181–Kuollut","1203–1267":"1203–1267","1177–Male":"1177–Kuollut","1203":"1203","1267":"1267","1177":"1177","1181":"1181","Neuerburg, Rheinland, Prussia":"Neuerburg, Kreis Bitburg, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Neu-Isenburg, Hesse-Nassau, Germany":"Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksa"},"fr":{"1177–":"1177–Décédé","1181–Female":"1181–Décédée","1203–1267":"1203–1267","1177–Male":"1177–Décédé","1203":"1203","1267":"1267","1177":"